The paper deals with distributed computing and message-passing models, which are typically studied in the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category. The use of combinatorial topology to derive lower bounds suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The study of communication constraints and graph properties may also be relevant to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The focus on closed-above models and the use of above-closure of graphs suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.NE (Networks and Communications) sub-category. Finally, the use of oblivious models and the study of underlying communication structures may also be relevant to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
